Reason:
These statements handle the configuration of triggers for downstream projects but do not check if the user has the necessary permissions to build those downstream projects before allowing the configuration to be saved. This oversight can lead to unauthorized build triggers, as users can configure downstream projects they are not permitted to build.

The code statements that fix the bug are:
```java
for (Publisher _t : Descriptor.newInstancesFromHeteroList(req, json, "publisher", Jenkins.getInstance().getExtensionList(BuildTrigger.DescriptorImpl.class))) {
    BuildTrigger t = (BuildTrigger) _t;
    for (AbstractProject downstream : t.getChildProjects(this)) {
        downstream.checkPermission(BUILD);
    }
}
```
Reason:
These statements introduce a permission check for each downstream project associated with the build trigger. By calling `downstream.checkPermission(BUILD)`, the code ensures that the user must have the appropriate permissions to build each downstream project before allowing the configuration to be saved, thus addressing the security vulnerability.

